metadata.name: Illusion City #245
metadata.description:
Illusion City reflects the variety of Istanbul by its different and divergent zones, day and night, humid summers and ice cold winters, colorful neighborhoods and giant plazas, its never ending human and vehicle traffic.

This series is an expression of how we experience this city, kind of like a love and hate relationship. The city that is a cradle of civilizations now has become a concrete jungle. Our beautiful city and its citizens are now trying to find their own balance in this state of chaos.

We wanted to express these complex emotions with a long-form generative artwork since it is the most suitable medium to explore every possible combination of emotions we have about our city. 

Best experienced in full screen.

Probabilities;

- 3 pre-made color palettes, 1 generative color palette

- 3 blend modes

- 3 topping placements

- 8 different particle angle compositions

- Several grid sizes and edges

- An intentionally kept in glitch (rare)

In live mode, press ‘s’ to save as .png (2000 x 2666 px )

It can take up to a minute to render or longer in low-performance computers. Enjoy the process!

Made with p5.js

Ilgın İçözü, July 2022
@distcollective

metadata.name: Momentary #345
metadata.description:
Sometimes, life's troubles seem to be immense and endless. They make us run around in despair, helplessly looking in every direction in search of an answer.

It's tough to be in control of those situations until we understand that everything in our life is momentary, the good times are momentary and of course the bad ones.

We tend to forget that life finds its way and that we just need to hold enough to start to see a clear path to follow.

Life is momentary, the good times are momentary and of course the bad ones.

Hold enough.

There is a path to follow.

-------
WARNING
Please, have into consideration that this work requires some CPU power due to the number of points that needs to be drawn on the canvas. Depending on the hardware and work features, the drawing could take some seconds to some minutes to be finished. 
-------

metadata.name: The Dreams of JSON Sakamojo #56
metadata.description:
"Do Androids Dream of Electric Sheep?", Phillip K. Dick

The year is 2121. JSON Sakamojo is a teenage boy in the Japanese town of Sendai. He is an android. All androids of his advanced type spend 3 years in a high school, where their neural networks complete their embodied cognitive training, and learn about the world and gain experience in socializing with humans and other androids (and gynoids).

Once a month, JSON meets with his AI trainer, who tracks his progress by downloading scans and engrammatic summaries of his recent experiences. These are in the form of dreams and reveries that are created when JSON's quantum brain undergoes daily information integration and long-term memory formation.

JSON, like many of his human classmates, mainly dreams of hanging out with his school friends, the girls of the school robotics club, and of being invited to join the local boy band "fSync".

These are some of his dream records...

(the (over 2200) images are generated by the AI program Craiyon).

metadata.name: Imoogi #17
metadata.description:
A hornless ocean dragon, sometimes equated with a sea serpent. Imoogi literally means, "Great Lizard". The legend of the Imoogi says that the sun god gave the Imoogi their power through a human girl, which would be transformed into the Imoogi on her 17th birthday. Legend also said that a dragon-shaped mark would be found on the shoulder of the girl, revealing that she was the Imoogi in human form.

- Press "S" to save an artwork.

metadata.name: Beyond #12
metadata.description:
This generative art token is a collaboration between artist Jaali Bandar and the NFT Museum of Newberry, SC. Jaali Bandar’s genesis fxhash project “Mona Lisa Overdrive” was one of the first NFTs acquired for the permanent collection. It was showcased at the NFT Museum’s #Cryptografik exhibition throughout the Spring of 2022. 

Jaali Bandar’s work quickly evolved to become fully immersive and interactive multimedia experiences (see Terra, What on Earth? and Terra Nova). In an effort to bring our worlds closer together, the NFT Museum of Newberry, SC reached out to Jaali Bandar of Bangalore, India to collaborate. This artwork explores the ethereal space where the real and the virtual meet. This is Beyond.  

We share 33% of future royalties with the original minters in an effort to encourage the promotion of fxhash artists and raise awareness of generative art on the blockchain. We want this art to spread far and wide. Thank you for your support in helping us accomplish this goal.


Token Details:

Beyond
Collab by Jaali Bandar x NFTMuseumSC
June 2022
fxhash Compliant NFT


Artist Bio: 

Jaali Bandar is an artist exploring the tech landscape in its anthropomorphic capacity as our collective moves towards a post-human condition. Coming from a design background he is exploring speculative fiction at the interactions of the meta, material and the virtual to create fictional representations using imagery, simulations and experiences.  


Artist Statement

As we let ourselves be overwhelmed by this omnipresent technological feedback, we change rapidly in more ways than we can fathom. As we approach the technological singularity, the question I ask is that how far can we see? As we complete the process of shifting our decision making burdens to the machines, all that remains are automated landscapes of our post-human desires and fragments of memories from a distant past. 

Beyond explores automated human exclusion zones with occasional glimpses of forgotten artifacts of the previous generation as a generative artwork. Diffusion reaction systems have this uncanny ability to morph perspectives as a function of visual feedback loops on the basis of visual inputs with varying degrees of control. 


Interactions:

- Press ‘p’ to show/hide cursor
- Press 's' to save .png 



Additional Credits and Attributions:

- Coded using Cables.gl : https://cables.gl/


About the NFT Museum of Newberry, SC:

Established in October of 2021, the mission of the Non-Fungible Token Museum is to provide a physical and virtual space for NFT art education, collaboration and exhibition in an effort to help our communities benefit from emerging blockchain technologies. Learn more at www.NonFungibleTokenMuseum.org

metadata.name: (Anti)thesis #38
metadata.description:
This is my first fxhash work. It is a generative, deterministic, object-oriented algorithm written entirely in p5.js. With the exception of two very rare background colours, the colour palettes are not pre-selected but entirely generated using your transaction hash.

The algorithm plays on the concept of Antithesis (/ænˈtɪθəsɪs/ - direct contrast; opposition) by using opposing forces to generate tension (and occasional calm) between forms on the page and the spaces in between. Inspiration was also drawn from works and advice from the great Daniel Catt (@revdancatt).

I hope you like it. Thanks for your support.
tallzy

metadata.name: Quantum Folly #114
metadata.description:
This piece explores humanity's vanity and obsession with controlling natural forces. In the end we are beholden to the whims of the universe and its rules. What we think is artificial is but nature's inclination.

As an atom gazes at the world it can see the arrogant hand of mankind imposing its will. We are nature's inane creation built from imperceptible, discrete particles.

Enjoy watching the structures form. Due to the nature of the system it may take some time to complete. Once it's fully rendered you can download a full resolution image of 3508 x 4961 px by ***double clicking/tapping***. At this size the piece is printable at A3 size at 300 dpi. If you're interested in acquiring a signed print please contact @KRANKARTA.

Features include: palette, orientation, architecture, particle rules, boundary seepage and colour displacement.

Created on Chrome desktop 103.0 on 2022-07-21 in javascript and GLSL. Results on other browsers/devices may vary.

metadata.name: Context-Free Wind #154
metadata.description:
Context-Free Wind is a poetry generator and visualizer created by Ross Goodwin (https://rossgoodwin.com) in vanilla JavaScript without the use of any framework or external libraries, excluding code required by fxhash. The generator uses a custom context-free grammar algorithm and word lists assembled by the creator to produce (...admittedly, fairly strange...) sentences.

These sentences are then blown aloft by a procedural "wind" -- based on the algorithm Goodwin first explored in the following Dweet:
https://www.dwitter.net/d/23927
